## 8. CLOUD RUN & NEXT.JS STANDALONE PRODUCTION CONSTRAINTS

- **Dynamic Scope Initialization:** Next.js `standalone` Docker builds aggressively cache globally scoped variables at module-load time. All third-party clients and AI SDK providers (e.g., `@ai-sdk/google`) MUST be initialized strictly *inside* the runtime request handler (e.g., inside `export async function POST`) to prevent caching build-time placeholder variables.
- **Explicit Provider Mapping:** Never rely on default or implicit environment variable hunting by third-party SDKs. Explicitly map the environment variable to the provider constructor (e.g., `createGoogleGenerativeAI({ apiKey: process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY })`).
- **Zero-Overwrite Deployment Scripts:** Infrastructure-as-Code scripts utilizing `gcloud run deploy` MUST NOT include `--set-env-vars` flags with placeholder values. Initial secret injection must be handled out-of-band or with real keys, and deploy scripts must allow the live container to retain its injected state.

---

## 9. GCP CLOUD RUN & MULTI-STAGE DOCKER PROTOCOL

- **The Multi-Stage Build Mandate:** All Next.js deployments to Google Cloud Run MUST use a strict 3-stage `Dockerfile` (`deps`, `builder`, `runner`). The `builder` stage MUST execute `npm run build` entirely inside the container to ensure `NEXT_PUBLIC_` variables are baked into the JavaScript bundle. Never use a runtime-only Dockerfile that copies a local `.next` folder.
- **Environment Variable Bifurcation:** Public Keys (`NEXT_PUBLIC_`) must live in `.env.production` and be COMMITTED to version control. The `.dockerignore` file MUST NOT ignore `.env.production`. Secret Keys (Gemini, DB Auth) MUST NEVER touch version control and must be injected securely at runtime.
- **Audit Before Deploy Check:** If a production deployment behaves differently than the local environment, you MUST halt execution and run an explicit audit of the `Dockerfile`, `.dockerignore`, and `deploy.sh` files to trace the build pipeline before proposing any code-level fixes.
